        <li>
          <p>
            If the rent were to be increased to <dollar />1000, how many occupied apartments would the
            apartment manager expect to have?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            At a <dollar />1000 monthly rent what net revenue should the apartment manager expect?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <hint>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Recall what we know about slope on a linear function.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Use the point slope form of the line.  You should have found the slope in
                part (a).
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Use your answer to part (b).
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                How do you get the accumulated payments from all of the tenants?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </hint>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The slope is
                <me>
                  m = \frac{196-203}{700-650} = -\frac{7}{50}
                </me>
                and this slope is consistent no matter which pairs of points we choose.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>A</m> be the number of occupied apartments and let <m>R</m> be the rent.  The
                linear function relating the number of occupied apartments and the rent is
                <me>
                  A - 203 = -\frac{7}{50} \left( R - 650 \right).
                </me>
                Solving for <m>A</m> we get
                <me>
                  A(R) = -\frac{7}{50} \left( R - 650 \right) + 203.
                </me>
                This is a perfectly acceptable algebraic form for the answer, but if you
                insist on simplifying then
                <me>
                  A(R) = -\frac{7}{50} R + 294.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A(1000) = -\frac{7}{50} \left( 1000 - 650 \right) + 203 = 252</m> units
                occupied.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The net revenue is the product of the monthly rent and the number of units
                occupied at that rent.  In this case the revenue is <m>\dollar1000 \cdot 252 =
                \dollar252,000</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The Old Farmer's Almanac tells us that you can tell the temperature by counting the chirps
          of a cricket. It is a linear function <m>T=f(C)</m> given by <m>T</m> (in degrees Fahrenheit)=<hash /> of
          chirps in 15 seconds <m>+40</m>. We can approximate this with the formula
          <me>
            T =  \frac{C}{4} + 40
          </me>
          where <m>C</m> is the number of chirps/minute and <m>T</m> is in <m>^\circ F</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                If the chirp rate is 120 chirps/minute, what is the temperature?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Suppose that crickets will not chirp if the temperature is below <m>56^\circ F</m>.
                We can also suppose that crickets will not chirp above <m>136^\circ F</m> since that is
                the highest temperature ever recorded at a weather station.  With these
                parameters, what is the domain of this function?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>C = 120</m> chirps/minute, substitute this into the function <m>T(C)</m> to obtain
          <me>
            T(120) = \frac{120}{4} + 40 = 30 + 40 = 70^\circ F.
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          To find the domain we need to find the appropriate values of <m>C</m> for the <m>T(C)</m>
          function.  Solve <m>56=C/4+40</m> and get <m>C = 64</m>.  Solve <m>136=C/4+40</m> and get <m>C =
          384</m>.  So the domain of <m>T(C)</m> is <m>64 \le \text{ chirps/minute }  \le 384</m> or, in
          interval notation, <m>[64, 136]</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Families of Linear Functions</title>
    <p>
      We noted above that a linear function has the form <m>f(x)=mx+b</m>, where <m>m</m> is the slope of
      the line, and <m>b</m> is the <m>y</m>-intercept. Since <m>m</m> and <m>b</m> can take on various values, taken
      together, they represent a family of functions. For example, we could fix <m>b = 2</m>, and then
      draw the graphs of <m>f(x)=mx+2</m> for various values of <m>m</m>; for example, <m>m = -1, -2, 2, 1</m>.
      Doing so would give the functions in the family <m>f(x)=mx+2</m> shown in the left image of <xref ref="fig_0_1_fam1">Figure</xref>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Similarly, we could set <m>m</m> to be <m>2</m> and let <m>b</m> take on the values <m>b=-1, 1, 4, -6</m> and
      we would get
      some examples from the family of functions for <m>y=f(x)=2x+b</m> shown in the right image of <xref ref="fig_0_1_fam1">Figure</xref>.
    </p>

    <p>
      From the right image in <xref ref="fig_0_1_fam1">Figure</xref> it should be clear to the reader that
      parallel lines have the same slope. What can you say about the slopes of perpendicular
      lines? Here is the result that we state without proof.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm_test">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If line <m>\ell_1</m> has slope <m>m_1</m> and line <m>\ell_2</m> has slope <m>m_2</m>, then
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                lines <m>\ell_1</m> and <m>\ell_2</m> are parallel if the slopes are the same: <m>m_1 = m_2</m>,
                and
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                lines <m>\ell_1</m> and <m>\ell_2</m> are perpendicular if the slopes are opposite
                reciprocals: <m>m_2 = -\frac{1}{m_1}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <figure xml:id="fig_0_1_fam1" >
      <caption>Several members of the family of linear functions <m>f(x) = mx+2</m> (left) and
      the family <m>f(x) = 2x+b</m> (right).</caption>
      <image width="90%" source="images/0-1-fig5.pdf" />
    </figure>

    <activity xml:id="A_0_1_4">
      <p>
        Write the equation of the line with the given information.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write the equation of a line parallel to the line <m>y=\frac{1}{2}x+3</m> passing through
              the point <m>(3,4)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Write the equation of a line perpendicular to the line <m>y=\frac{1}{2}x + 3</m> passing
              through the point <m>(3,4)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Write the equation of a line with <m>y</m>-intercept <m>(0,-3)</m> that is perpendicular to
              the line <m>y=-3x-1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <hint>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the slope of the line that you're given and which form of a linear
                function would be most convenient?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                What is the slope of the line that you're given and which form of a linear
                function would be most convenient?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                You are given the <m>y</m>-intercept.  Why is that a special case?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </hint>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The slope is <m>m = \frac{1}{2}</m> and you have a point so use the point-slope
                form of the line to get
                <me>
                  y - 4 = \frac{1}{2} \left( x-3 \right).
                </me>
                Solving for <m>y</m> we get
                <me>
                  y = \frac{1}{2} \left( x-3 \right) + 4.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The slope is <m>m = -2</m> and we have a point so use the point-slope form of the
                line to get
                <me>
                  y - 4 = -2 (x-3).
                </me>
                Solving for <m>y</m> we get
                <me>
                  y = -2(x-3) + 4.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The slope is <m>m = \frac{1}{3}</m> and since we have the <m>y</m>-intercept we know
                that the slope-intercept for the line is the proper choice.  Hence,
                <me>
                  y = \frac{1}{3} x - 3.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Summary</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          A function assigns one <m>y</m> value to each <m>x</m> value.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The slope of a linear function can be written as
          <me>
            m = \frac{\text{ Rise } }{\text{ Run } } = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_2}
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          A linear function can be written in the forms
          <me>
            y = mx + b  \text{ or }   y-y_1 = m(x-x_1)
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          When examining linear data, the differences between successive <m>y</m>-values reveals
          the slope.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
